**Abstract:**
Working notes dated August 4, 1993 for article related to Chantilly project. Discusses Aquinas's interpretation of Aristotle, the "revolt of logos against muthos" (Curtius, via de Lubac), and the distinction between spoken and written language. Develops argument that language incarnates communicative intentions between exposed agents, not between invulnerable contemplators. Contrasts performative speech acts of vulnerable agents with the purely factual/descriptive language philosophers aspire to.

